generation in Late Second Millennium Southwest Canaan -- t13. A False Contrast? On the Possibility of an Early Iron Age Nomadic Monarchy in the Arabah (Early Edom) and Its Implications for the Study of Ancient Israel -- t14. The Book of Josiah or the Book of Joshua? Excavating the Literary History of the Conquest Story -- t15. The Origin, Function and Disappearance of the Ark of the Covenant according to the Hebrew Bible -- t16. The Scope of the Pre-Deuteronomistic Saul–David Story Cycle -- t17. The Rise of Ancient Israel: The View from 2021 -- tIndex of Geographic Names -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Modern Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArchaeological exploration in the Central Highlands of the Southern Levant conducted during the 1970s and 1980s dramatically transformed the scholarly understanding of the early Iron Age and led to the publication of From Nomadism to Monarchy: Archaeological and Historical Aspects of Early Israel, by Israel Finkelstein and Nadav Na’aman. This volume explores and reassesses the legacy of that foundational text. Using current theoretical frameworks and taking into account new excavation data and methodologies from the natural sciences, the seventeen essays in this volume examine the archaeology of the Southern Levant during the early Iron Age and the ways in which the period may be reflected in biblical accounts. The variety of methodologies employed and the historical narratives presented within these contributions illuminate the multifaceted nature of contemporary research on this formative period.Building upon Finkelstein and Na’aman’s seminal study, this work provides an essential update. It will be welcomed by ancient historians, scholars of early Israel and the early Iron Age Southern Levant, and biblical scholars. In addition to the editors, the contributors to this volume are Eran Arie, Erez Ben-Yosef, Cynthia Edenburg, Israel Finkelstein, Yuval Gadot, Assaf Kleiman, Gunnar Lehmann, Defna Langgut, Aren M. Maeir, Nadav Na’aman, Thomas Römer, Lidar Sapir-Hen, Katja Soennecken, Dieter Vieweger, Ido Wachtel, and Naama Yahalom-Mack.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zMiddle East. 0aIron agezMiddle East. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  abiblical accounts.  acentral highlands of the Southern Levant.  airon age archaeology.  aupdate to From Nomadism to Monarchy: Archaeological and Historical Aspects of Early Israel.1 aArie, Eran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Yosef, Erez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdenburg, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinkelstein, Israel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGadot, Yuval, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKleiman, Assaf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoch, Ido, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoch, Ido, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLanggut, Dafna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehmann, Gunnar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipschits, Oded, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipschits, Oded, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMaeir, Aren M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaʾaman, Nadav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRömer, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSapir-Hen, Lidar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/